        "text": "Some great points have already been made. Here a few others.\n\nAdvantages of DSLM:\n• More flexible in terms of light sheet height.\n• More even illumination across the height\n• Possibility of slit detection, but this does not really work across large samples as the slit size is very critical (either no effect or loss of signal). Definitely a loss of signal along beam propagation as the beam is scattered, leading to uneven illumination. \n• Some people claim that striping is reduced, but I am not sure about this. \nAdvantages of SPIM:\n• Cheaper (cylindrical lens vs. galvo) and easier to build\/align\n• Lower peak power and, therefore, gentler on the samples and much less likely to saturate the fluorophores\n• It can be arbitrarily fast. No need to scan, and one can strobe the sheet if you want to freeze motion.  The framerate depends only on the camera.\n• Easier to implement mSPIM (pivoting of the light sheet to reduce striping)",
